  • Method Details

    • consecutivePairs

      public static <T> java.util.List<PairOfSameType<T>> consecutivePairs​(java.lang.Iterable<T> inner)
      This allows you to walk over an iterable 2 consecutive items at a time and not have to worry about saving the 1st item as 'previous' and remembering to update it. E.g. if 'inner' is A, B, C, D, then the list will have (A, B), (B, C), and (C, D). Since we're building a list, we might as well return a list instead of an Iterable, since the list has extra conveniences.

    • consecutiveNonOverlappingPairs

      public static <T> java.util.List<PairOfSameType<T>> consecutiveNonOverlappingPairs​(java.lang.Iterable<T> inner)
      This allows you to walk over an iterable 2 consecutive items at a time (with no overlap) and not have to worry about saving the 1st item as 'previous' and remembering to update it. E.g. if 'inner' is A, B, C, D, E, F, then the list will have (A, B), (C, D), (E, F). Since we're building a list, we might as well return a list instead of an Iterable, since the list has extra conveniences.

    • allPairsMatch

      public static <T1,​ T2> boolean allPairsMatch​(java.lang.Iterable<T1> iter1, java.lang.Iterable<T2> iter2, java.util.function.BiPredicate<T1,​T2> biPredicate)
      Returns true if each pair of values in 2 iterables returns true for the supplied BiPredicate.

      It will also have a precondition that they have the same number of items.

      This is useful for situations where we want a partial equality (i.e. not compare every member), or where there's no equality operation that's well-defined enough to add as a method in the data class, which is something we usually avoid to do. One rare example is if the data class stores verb classes in it, which cannot really be compared, except for their Class object.

      The name parallels Stream.allMatch(Predicate). That is, this is unrelated to the test hamcrest matchers.

    • getOnlyIndexWhere

      public static <T> int getOnlyIndexWhere​(java.lang.Iterable<T> iterable, java.util.function.Predicate<T> predicate)
      Finds the first item in an iterator that satisfies a condition, and returns its position in the iterator (0, 1, etc.) Throws if condition applies to 0, or more than 1 item.

    • forEachUnequalPairInList

      public static <K> void forEachUnequalPairInList​(java.util.List<K> list, java.util.function.BiConsumer<K,​K> biConsumer)
      E.g. if you pass in keys A, B, C, D, this will operate on AB, AC, AD, BC, BD, CD. It expressly avoids looking at any pair (X, X), hence 'unique' (though that's not a great adjective here).

    • forEachUniquePair

      public static <K> void forEachUniquePair​(java.lang.Iterable<K> keys, java.util.function.BiConsumer<K,​K> biConsumer)
      E.g. if you pass in keys A, B, C, D, this will operate on AB/BA, AC/CA, AD/DA, BC/CB, BD/DB, CD/DC. It expressly avoids looking at any pair (X, X), hence 'unique' (though that's not a great adjective here).
